Put a large #saucepan{} of water with a generous pinch of @salt{pinch} on to boil for the pasta. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch} (stalks and all). Chop the @vine tomatoes{2%medium} into 2cm cubes.

Add the @spaghetti{250%g} to your pan of boiling water and cook for ~{11%minutes} or until 'al dente'.

> 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

Once cooked, drain the pasta in a #colander{} (keep a little of the pasta water to one side in case the sauce is too thick) and drizzle with a little @oil{} to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a little @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Add the @chorizo{60%g} and stir-fry until slightly crispy, ~{3%minutes}.

Add the garlic and a small pinch of @chilli flakes{1/2%tsp}. Cook for ~{30%seconds}.

> Some like it hot, but if that's not you then go easy on the chilli!

Add the @king prawns{120}. Stir together and cook for a further ~{2-3%minutes}.

Pour in the @tomato passata{1%small jar}. Let the mixture simmer on medium heat for ~{5%minutes}. Add the vine tomato. Cook for ~{1%minute} more. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and plenty of @black pepper{plenty}.

> The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque all the way through.

Drain the pasta in a colander and add it to the pan with the sauce.

> If the sauce is too thick at this point, loosen it up with a splash of the pasta water.

Toss everything together. Divide between #bowls{} and finish with a sprinkling of parsley. Enjoy!